{"id":"historic-columbia-river-highway","generatedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z","designation":"All-American Road","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Historic Columbia River Highway","revisionId":1336763910,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Historic_Columbia_River_Highway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Historic_Columbia_River_Highway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Historic Columbia River Highway\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Historic_Columbia_River_Highway","revisionId":1336763910,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"}],"endpoints":null,"itinerary":[{"place":"Historic Columbia River Highway (start)","mileFromStart":0,"kind":"terminus","lat":45.69045,"lng":-121.68824,"seq":1,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"The drive begins here","toNextMi":0.7},{"place":"Hole-in-the-Wall Falls","mileFromStart":0.7,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.68612,"lng":-121.70205,"seq":2,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.2},{"place":"Lower Lancaster Falls","mileFromStart":0.9,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.68488,"lng":-121.70611,"seq":3,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.5},{"place":"Harrison Falls","mileFromStart":1.4,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.68672,"lng":-121.71621,"seq":4,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.7},{"place":"Camp Benson Falls","mileFromStart":2.1,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.68828,"lng":-121.7281,"seq":5,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":10.7},{"place":"Lower Ruckel Creek Falls","mileFromStart":12.8,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.64503,"lng":-121.91877,"seq":6,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.2},{"place":"Buck Point","mileFromStart":13,"kind":"overlook","lat":45.64093,"lng":-121.91853,"seq":7,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.5},{"place":"Wauna Viewpoint","mileFromStart":13.5,"kind":"overlook","lat":45.63702,"lng":-121.92806,"seq":8,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":10.1},{"place":"Scenic overlook","mileFromStart":23.6,"kind":"overlook","lat":45.57587,"lng":-122.11506,"seq":9,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0},{"place":"Lower Multnomah Falls","mileFromStart":23.6,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.5766,"lng":-122.1161,"seq":10,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0},{"place":"Multnomah Falls","mileFromStart":23.6,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.57595,"lng":-122.11519,"seq":11,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.5},{"place":"Lemmons Viewpoint","mileFromStart":24.1,"kind":"overlook","lat":45.57404,"lng":-122.12658,"seq":12,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":3.2},{"place":"Bridal Veil Falls","mileFromStart":27.3,"kind":"crossing","lat":45.55446,"lng":-122.18024,"seq":13,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":3.2},{"place":"Crown point","mileFromStart":30.5,"kind":"overlook","lat":45.53968,"lng":-122.24426,"seq":14,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.8},{"place":"Portland Women's Forum State Scenic Viewpoint","mileFromStart":31.3,"kind":"overlook","lat":45.53478,"lng":-122.26058,"seq":15,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":43.5},{"place":"Historic Columbia River Highway (end)","mileFromStart":74.8,"kind":"terminus","lat":45.5463,"lng":-122.22588,"seq":16,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"The drive ends here"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["The Columbia River Gorge is the lowest crossing of the Cascade Mountains, carved by the Columbia River during the Cascades' uplift. Rafting down the gorge from The Dalles was one of the most expensive and dangerous parts of the Oregon Trail, traveled by thousands of emigrants to the Oregon Territory, until the Barlow Road opened in 1846 around the south side of Mount Hood. A wagon road was finally built through the gorge in the 1870s, when The Dalles and Sandy Wagon Road was constructed along the south shore from The Dalles to the Sandy River east of Portland. However, this road had steep (20%) grades and a crooked and narrow alignment, and it was not until 1882 that the Oregon Railway and Navigation Company finally opened a water-level route, partially destroying the wagon road. With the onset of the automobile and the good roads movement of the early 20th century, a road was once again needed, and Multnomah County began constructing a 20-foot (6 m) roadway with 9% grades, but ran into difficulties relating to the railroad's location. At Shellrock Mountain to the east, long believed to be an impassable barrier, Governor Oswald West used prison labor in 1912 to prove that it was possible to build a road, at least temporarily.","The eventual highway was primarily designed by engineer and landscape architect Samuel C. Lancaster, a lifelong friend of good roads promoter Samuel Hill. His first contribution to the Pacific Northwest was as a consultant for Seattle's Olmsted boulevard system, part of its preparations for the 1909 Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition. In 1908, the two traveled to Europe for the First International Road Congress, where Hill represented the state of Washington. Hill was especially impressed by Switzerland's Axenstrasse, a road built along Lake Lucerne in 1865 that included a windowed tunnel, and wanted to build a similar scenic highway through the Columbia River Gorge. With Lancaster's help, Hill built the experimental Maryhill Loops Road from the river east of the gorge up the Columbia Hills to his planned Quaker utopian community at Maryhill. The road was the first asphalt road in the state, designed with gradual horseshoe curves to avoid steep grades. However, Washington's lawmakers denied his request for a cross-state trunk route on the river's north bank, and Hill crossed the river to Oregon, the last of the states in the far Western U.S. to create a highway department. With the help of his life-size model at Maryhill, he convinced the state legislature to create the State Highway Commission in 1913, which would work with the counties to build roads. The Multnomah County commissioners agreed later that year that the state should design the route to distance it from county politics, and set aside an initial $75,000.","In laying out the highway, Lancaster sought not only to create a transportation artery, but to make the gorge's \"beautiful waterfalls, canyons, cliffs and mountain domes\" accessible to \"men from all climes\". According to locating engineer John Arthur Elliott,","Lancaster began surveying near the Chanticleer Inn, where Larch Mountain Road, part of Multnomah County's existing road network, began climbing the hills of the gorge. For five months, from September 1913 to January 1914, he laid out a route for about 21 miles (34 km) to the Hood River County line west of Cascade Locks. The alignment generally had a maximum grade of 5% and curve radius of 200 feet (61 m), and was wide enough for 18 feet (5.5 m) of macadam (later asphalt) and two 3-foot (0.91 m) gravel shoulders. To accomplish this, Lancaster used curves similar to the road he had designed at Maryhill where the highway descended from Crown Point."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Oregon Department of Transportation. \"Public Road Inventory\". Oregon Department of Transportation. Archived from the original on February 24, 2008. Retrieved January 2, 2017.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20080224153306/http://www.oregon.gov/ODOT/TD/TDATA/rics/PublicRoadsInventory.shtml"},{"n":2,"text":"\"National Register Information System\". National Register of Historic Places. National Park Service. July 9, 2010. Retrieved September 29, 2013.","url":"https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP"},{"n":3,"text":"National Park Service (n.d.). \"Listing of National Historic Landmarks by State: Oregon\" (PDF). National Park Service. Archived from the original (PDF) on September 19, 2016. Retrieved June 29, 2014.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20160919115759/https://www.nps.gov/nhl/find/statelists/or/OR.pdf"},{"n":4,"text":"Federal Highway Administration (n.d.). \"America's Byways Fact Sheet\". America's Byways. Federal Highway Administration. Archived from the original on May 8, 2013. Retrieved January 2, 2017.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20130508181404/http://byways.org/press/fact_sheet.html"},{"n":5,"text":"Cascades Volcano Observatory. The Geologic History of the Columbia River Gorge (Brochure). United States Geological Survey. Retrieved March 26, 2018.","url":"https://vulcan.wr.usgs.gov/Volcanoes/Washington/ColumbiaRiver/geo_history_gorge.html"},{"n":6,"text":"Rusler, Renee (May 25, 2004). \"Barlow Road\". Whitman Mission NHS: History & Culture. National Park Service. Archived from the original on January 25, 2007. Retrieved March 26, 2018.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20070125064519/http://www.nps.gov/archive/whmi/educate/ortrtg/1or13.htm"},{"n":7,"text":"Hadlow, Robert W. (February 4, 2000). National Historic Landmark Nomination: Columbia River Highway (Report). Oregon Department of Transportation. pp. 57–58. Archived from the original on March 27, 2008.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20080327141256/http://www.oregon.gov/ODOT/HWY/HCRH/documents.shtml"},{"n":8,"text":"Hadlow (2000), pp. 47–56, 58–60","url":""}],"routeLine":[[45.69045,-121.68824],[45.68938,-121.68974],[45.6886,-121.69154],[45.68817,-121.69296],[45.68793,-121.69407],[45.68776,-121.69509],[4